{
  "doc_id": "52635",
  "text": "Monocytes are produced in the bone marrow and circulate in blood for 24-48 hours [CITATION_1] . In the absence of serum, monocytes die via apoptosis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Macrophage colony-stimulating factor (M-CSF) stimulates mononuclear phagocyte survival and differentiation [CITATION_4] . Importantly, M-CSF-mediated cell survival and activation is associated with a variety of human diseases, including atherosclerosis, transplant vascular sclerosis and breast cancer metastasis [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
